# Git Fundamentals & Advanced Concepts Guide

---

**1. What is Git?**
Git is a distributed version control system:

* Every developer has a complete copy of the repository
* Includes full code, history, and metadata (who committed what and when)

---

**2. Initial Git Setup**

```
git init
```

Initialize a new Git repository

```
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your.email@example.com"
```

Set global username and email

```
git remote add origin <github_url_of_repo>
```

Link local repository to GitHub

---

**3. Basic Workflow Commands**

```
git add .
```

Stage all changes

```
git commit -m <message>
```

Commit staged changes

```
git push -u origin main
```

Push commits to remote repository

---

**4. Branching & Navigation**

```
git branch <branch-name>
```

Create a new branch

```
git checkout <branch-name>
```

Switch to a branch

```
git checkout -b <branch-name>
```

Create and switch to a new branch

---

**5. Working with Commits**

```
git checkout <commit-hash>
```

Move to a specific commit

* Causes a detached HEAD state
* HEAD points to a commit instead of a branch
* No commits are deleted

---

**6. Relative References (Refs)**

* `^` → Move one commit up
* `~<num>` → Move multiple commits up

Examples:

```
main^
main^^
HEAD^
```

```
git checkout <c3>
git checkout HEAD^
```

---

**7. Branch Forcing**

```
git branch -f main HEAD~3
```

Forcefully move the main branch 3 commits back

---

**8. Reset vs Revert**

git reset (rewrites history)

```
git reset --soft <commit-hash>
```

Keeps changes staged

```
git reset <commit-id>
```

Mixed reset (default) → keeps changes unstaged

```
git reset --hard <commit-id>
```

Deletes all changes after the commit

---

git revert (safe undo)

```
git revert <commit-id>
```

Creates a new commit that undoes changes

If conflicts occur:

```
git add .
git revert --continue
```

---

**9. Git Stash**

```
git stash
```

Save uncommitted changes

```
git status list
```

List all stashes

```
git stash apply stash@{0}
```

Apply a stash

---

**10. Rebasing**

Rebasing copies commits and reapplies them to create a linear history

Example:

Before:

```
c0
 |
c1 <- main
 |
c2 <- feature-branch*
```

After:

```
c0
 |
c1
 |
c2 <- main*, feature-branch
```

---

**11. Interactive Rebase**

Allows:

* Change commit message
* Delete commits
* Reorder commits
* Combine commits
* Split/edit commits

WARNING: Do not use on pushed/shared commits

```
git rebase -i HEAD~3
```

To change commit message:

* Replace `pick` with `reword`

---

**12. Squashing Commits**

Use:

```
squash
```

Combines a commit with the previous one

---

**13. Viewing History**

```
