23. Remote Branches

Remote branches represent the state of a remote repository as of the last time you synced.

Help compare:
Your local work
Work available on the remote
Exist locally, not on the remote itself
Typically prefixed (e.g., origin/main, often written as o/main)

Key Behavior

When you check out a remote branch → Git puts you in detached HEAD mode
You cannot directly commit to a remote branch
You must:
Work on a local branch
Then push changes to the remote

---

24. What git fetch Does

git fetch

Performs two main actions:

Downloads commits from remote that are missing locally
Updates remote-tracking branches (e.g., origin/main / o/main)

Important Notes

Does NOT modify your working directory
Does NOT merge changes automatically
Simply updates your local view of the remote repository

---

25. Working with Fetched Changes

After fetching, you can integrate changes using standard Git commands:

git cherry-pick o/main
git rebase o/main
git merge o/main

---

26. git pull with Rebase

git pull --rebase
git push

Explanation:

git pull --rebase:
Fetches latest changes from remote
Rebases your local commits on top of updated remote branch
Keeps history clean and linear
After resolving conflicts (if any), push changes using git push

---

27. Tracking Remote Branches

You can configure any local branch to track a remote branch.

A tracking branch has:
Default pull target
Default push destination
This allows commands like git push and git pull to work without specifying a branch

Key Concept

A branch does NOT need to have the same name as the remote branch it tracks.

Example:

A branch named totallyNotMain can track o/main
Running git push from totallyNotMain will push to remote main

Method 1: Create a Tracking Branch While Checking Out

git checkout -b totallyNotMain o/main
Creates a new branch totallyNotMain
Automatically sets it to track o/main

Method 2: Set Tracking Using git branch -u

git branch -u o/main foo
Sets branch foo to track o/main

If the branch is already checked out:

git branch -u o/main
Sets current branch to track o/main


To push a branch commit to another branch
git push origin sourcebranch:destbranch

Pushing nothing will delete the branch 
git push origin :foo

Fetching nothing will create the branch
git fetch origin :bar